                                <foliation>The quire is foliated with the numbers 1-4, in Arabic
                                    numerals, in pencil, recto, upper right.</foliation>

                                <collation>
                                    <p>The fragment consists of 2 bifolios, probably the inner half
                                        of a quaternion.</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <list>
                                            <item>Quire 1<hi rend="superscript">8-4</hi>
                                                <locus from="1r" to="4v"> ff. 1-4 </locus>
                                                <note>The first, second, seventh and eighth folios
                                                  have probably been lost, with loss of
                                                text</note>
                                 </item>
                                        </list>
                                    </p>
                                </collation>

                                <condition>The lower part of all folios has been torn away,
                                    amounting to more than half of the total area in all cases, and
                                    the vast majority of <locus from="4r" to="4v">f. 4</locus>.
                                    There is mild water staining and areas of dirt.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>

                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout cert="low" columns="2" rulingMedium="hardpoint" topLine="below" writtenLines="12 27">Two columns of up to 12 lines each,
                                    probably originally totalling about 27 lines. The Greek text
                                    appears in the left-hand column, the Arabic on the right. 
                                    <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                                        <height max="93" min="74">74-93</height>
                                        <width quantity="130">130</width>
                                    </dimensions>
                                    <note>The original height of the written area was probably
                                        approximately 200 mm. </note>
                                    <seg type="pricking">Pricking does not survive. </seg>
                                    <seg type="ruling">Ruled in hardpoint, system probably Leroy 1,
                                        type probably Leroy <formula notation="Leroy">24D2</formula>
                                        or <formula notation="Leroy">22D2a</formula> (two horizontal
                                        lines appear in the upper margin; the number in the lower
                                        margin is unclear).</seg>
                                </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>

                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote scope="major" xml:id="hand-1">
                                <p>The Greek text was copied by Hand A in an upright <term type="script">mixed minuscule</term> script, in dark brown
                                    ink, with minimal variation in letter size.</p>
                                <p>Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings do not
                                    appear. Breathings are angular, and mute <hi rend="italic">iota</hi> is absent or adscript. Use of the double dot is
                                    functional only and <foreign xml:lang="la">nomina
                                        sacra</foreign> are unaccentuated. The double grave accent
                                    is in use.</p>
                                <p>Punctuation used includes the upper point and full stop.</p>
                                <p>Headings have been added in <term type="script">Alexandrine
                                        majuscule</term> script, in red ink.</p>
                            </handNote>

                            <handNote scope="major" xml:id="hand-2">
                                <p>The Arabic text was copied by Hand A in pale brown ink, sometimes
                                    overwritten in black. Headings have been added in red ink.</p>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>

                        <additions>Modern chapter and verse numbers for the beginning and end of the
                            text on each folio or of a new lection have been added, along with a
                            note of the end of the last lection in Greek. The fragment has been
                            marked with the present classmark and the former classmark
                            T.35.</additions>

                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding calendar="gregorian" when="2019">
                                <p> The fragment has a modern card binding reinforced with cloth
                                    inside the spine.</p>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>

                    <history>
                        <origin>The style of script suggests that the fragment was probably copied
                            in the <origDate calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1099" notBefore="1000">11th century</origDate>. The bilingual content would suggest that
                            it was produced in an Arabic-speaking region in the <origPlace key="place_g7593196">eastern Mediterranean</origPlace>.</origin>

